text: Nice concept and delivery. So each character represents Joy, Sadness, Fear, Anger and Disgust.  The father seems to be led by Anger. The mother by Sadness. The daughter seems to be led by Disgust and Anger that are influenced by Fear. It's interesting how Joy and Sadness are not present in the little girls head, as if she is bottling and locking those emotions down, somewhere inside her. This is unhealthy and makes her imbalanced.  This is a nice perspective for kids to look at. It simplifies emotions that are quite complex. This is interesting. Pixar's good.

text: Dear anyone going: "This looks anti-men", it's also anti-women too.  ;)  Yes, the dad's a stereotypical nonresponsive idiot with respect issues, and it's a really old and stupid trope.  But the mom's also a "higher than thou, I'm not going to try to bring you into the conversation and assume you can mind-read, OMG I want to bone that hot guy and have the kind of mindset that leads to relationship-crushing affairs with the hot surfer guy in town" idiot.  Which is arguably the worse portrayal.  The movie seems more like it's making fun of and calling out the previous generation of parents and saying "HEY.  Both of you are total self-centered pricks.  Get the hell over yourselves and actually TRY to connect with your daughter.  And the parents of the kids in the theater now?  GET OVER YOURSELVES TOO.  Don't be like these two jerks!"  And I was wondering if this was going to be about the girl having some kind of gender-identity issue (since she seems to have 2 male thingies in her head), or be dealing with some kind of mental-health problem, but apparently that's not the plot.  It's supposedly just her adjusting to moving to a new state and dealing with her self-centered parents.  Bah.  This could have been a mindblowing movie, and instead, it takes the safe route.  :(

text: You know, even though this seems like a purely stereotypical way of looking at how people think, since this is Pixar I think (and hope) that they have more up their sleeves.  I actually think it would be cool if they start it off like each character looks like a cardboard cutout of their gender/age/family position stereotype, but gradually as the movie goes on, reveals that each of them, even their inner voices/personality parts, are far more complex and deep than others think.  The lesson would probably be to be careful about thinking you know everything about why someone does something, when in fact, they have many other reasons.  Maybe not good reasons, but people are not cardboard cutouts.  I just think that this is a viable possibility.  Let's hope Pixar can make another gem.

text: I dont know why people didn't like this. I thought it was extremely good way to show kids how little things build up if they dont talk about things especially things that they dont realise are causing them to unknowingly feel stressed, disappointed and depressed. They just feel down and dont realise that left bottled up it can lead to a complete breakdown of everything in their life. How depression takes hold and can slowly destroy any happy memories, make them forget good times with friends and family. Make them give up sports they loved to play and how depression draws them into thinking nothing in their life is good. That brings anger, disgust and sadness. I honestly think all kids should watch this with their parents or families and discuss wot happened afterwards. Could possibly help stop some young people committing suicide
author: heather wallace

text: If u discuss how u feel is the beginning of Being able to start feeling good and feeling happy again. Little pick me ups can start to reduce the sadness. It's different for everyone, different triggers and reasons. Just some people are able to ask for help. Others can't or dont know how to or feel they have none that can help. Some people just think its life deal with it or try to forget. It will go away. It won't. they will slowly get sadder, find more things they start to feel unhappy about until they let it take over everything in their life, most the time without really knowing it's happening.  Everyone can get some help from somewhere or someone it's just knowing how to get it, how to ask for help and who to ask
author: heather wallace

text: Call ur mates if u havent done so in a while. If u leave messages and never get replies dont think they dont want to talk to u or see u. There is usually something that's changed in their life and they may need you to lean on but ask. They dont reply because they know u know them well enough to pick up that something is wrong. They may not be ready to talk, so just keep calling. Keep going to see them. They will eventually start to disclose things so listen,  offer advice no matter how unimportant or unhelpful u think that advice will be. To the person suffering depression every friend that really listens,  offers advice and shows they care enough to listen to their smallest problems is the person they will finally open up to.
author: heather wallace
